thoughts.a: The input and output grids are the same sizes. The input grid has a supergrid of objects where the object is a 4x4 tile square made up of a green tile edge and a red, yellow, or aqua tile interior. This super grid exists on a black color background, and does not necessarily show all the objects at the edge. That is, the edge of the input grid might clip some of the supergrid objects. The output grid is very similar looking to the input grid, with the exception that some of the connections between certain supergrid objects have changed color from the background color to the tile interior color. For example, we see in the output grid that some of the black color background tiles that are located between the yellow interior supergrid objects are now changed to yellow, acting as a sort of conduit or channel across the supergrid, connecting the yellow interior objects. The same is true for the aqua interior objects. We notice that the conduits are only created on the black color background tiles and not of any of the interior tiles that the conduit passes through. The conduits are acting as if they are passing under the red interior supergrid objects. Thus the hypthosis is the following. The input grid will contain a super grid of similar colored objects, where some objects may be clipped off by the edge of the input grid. Each object's outer layer will contain the same color. In this case, it's green. The supergrid objects interior color will be some other color, probably red, yellow, or aqua. In order to construct the output grid, we need to copy over the input grid as is but change some specific background tiles from the background color of black to a specific interior object color. We effectively need to build conduits from any pair of like interior colors that are the most common interior color, which in this case is red. These conduits are made by changing the tiles to the color of the interior, but only in the background color tiles and not on the edge or the interior of any of the supergrid shaped object. In this case, we have two sets of non-red color tiles, so we must make the conduits the appropriate colors where necessary. The conduits are built between any two horizontal or vertical pairs of non-red interior objects, and only in the rows or columns that the interior colors exist in the supergrid.
thoughts.b: The input and output grids are, again, the same sizes. The input grid has a super grid of objects where the object is a three by three tile square made up of a single tile layer of red for the edge and a blue, green, or yellow tile interior. This super grid exists on a black color background and does not necessarily show completely all of the objects at the edge. We notice that the most common interior grid tile color is yellow. According to the hypothesis, in order to construct the output grid, we need to copy over the input grid as is to the output grid and in addition we need to effectively build conduits between any supergrid object that does not contain the most common interior tile color. In this case, the most common interior tile color is yellow, so we should not be building any yellow conduits. However, there are green and blue interior color objects, and between any of these we need to change the black color background tiles to their corresponding green and blue colors for the conduit. The conduit should be only as wide or tall as the interior color, which in this case is 1 tile wide or tall. The conduit should only change the black color background tiles and can go otherwise go through the yellow interior supergrid objects in order to connect the similar color interior objects. Because this is exactly what we see in the output grid, the hypothesis holds.

In this case, the interior tile is 1 tile, so the conduits will be 1 tile wide or tall. The conduit should only change the black color background tiles and can otherwise go through the red interior supergrid objects in order to connect the similar color interior objects. Because this is exactly what we see in the output grid of the hypothesis holds.
